<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="112" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d112">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.811/127a</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Minister <persName type="to">Reinsch</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-18">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 18, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Chinese Minister for Foreign Affairs has telegraphed Legation here
                            that there is misunderstanding as to preliminary survey of the Hwai
                            River, saying Wai Chiao Pu never agreed to assume whole expense and that
                            you informed him that Red Cross expected to be reimbursed amount of its
                            contribution. Inform Wai Chiao Pu that the Red Cross is willing to
                            contribute up to $50,000 gold without repayment if no loan made and,
                            with or without J. G. White Company, will advance the balance up to
                            $100,000 with understanding that such balance is to be refunded.</p>
                        <p>Three eminent engineers, Sibert chairman, will leave for China about June
                            first.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>